User:

working of unary increment operarator in c

Assistant:

The unary increment operator (`++`) in C is used to increase the value of a variable by 1. It can be used in two different ways: as a prefix operator (e.g. `++i`) or as a postfix operator (e.g. `i++`).

Here is an example of how the unary increment operator can be used:
```
#include <stdio.h>

int main(void)
{
    int i = 0;
    printf("i = %d\n", i);  // prints "i = 0"

    ++i;  // increment i by 1
    printf("i = %d\n", i);  // prints "i = 1"

    i++;  // increment i by 1
    printf("i = %d\n", i);  // prints "i = 2"

    return 0;
}
```
As you can see, the unary increment operator increases the value of `i` by 1 each time it is used.

When used as a prefix operator (e.g. `++i`), the increment is applied before the value of the variable is used in the expression. When used as a postfix operator (e.g. `i++`), the increment is applied after the value of the variable is used in the expression.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions.

